The paper focuses on the use of artificial intelligence models, specifically deep learning techniques, for the detection of atrial fibrillation in electrocardiograms. This suggests that the paper is likely to fall under the machine learning (cs.LG) and computer vision (cs.CV) sub-categories. Additionally, the use of convolutional and recurrent network architectures indicates that the paper may also fall under the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category. The paper also involves the extraction of significant time and frequency domain characteristics of the ECG signal, which suggests that it may fall under the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the evaluation of the classification approaches against the MIT-BIH AFIB dataset, which suggests that it may also fall under the human-computer interaction (cs.HC) sub-category.
